---
/**
 * src/pages/index.astro
 * =====================
 * Homepage â€” migrated from /index.html
 *
 * What changed:
 *  - No more runtime fetch() for top-bar, logo, footer, highlights
 *  - All components are imported via BaseLayout at build time
 *  - Page-specific styles use <style> in the head slot
 *  - Page-specific scripts go in the scripts slot
 */
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import Banner from "../components/Banner.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Home"
  description="This is the homepage"
  activeButton="Home-button"
>
  <!-- Extra page-specific styles -->
  <Fragment slot="head">
    <style>
      @media all and (max-width: 580px) {
        #chladniImage {
          width: 95% !important;
        }
        #chladni-outer-div {
          padding-top: 25px;
        }
      }
      .repo {
        padding: 20px;
        border: 1px solid #ddd;
        border-radius: 5px;
        margin: 5px 0;
      }
      .calendar {
        padding: 20px;
      }
    </style>
  </Fragment>

  <!-- Page content (same HTML as before, minus the boilerplate) -->
  <Banner />

  <div class="content-grid" id="home">
    <header>
      <div class="topic">Homepage</div>
    </header>

    <section>
      <h1 class="home-title">Chladni Patterns - The Wave Equation Model</h1>
      <div class="two-columns-block">
        <div>
          <p>
            Take a solid metal plate (or any other rigid material) and sprinkle
            some particles on it. It can either be sand, salt, or even baking
            soda. Then, generate some vibration on the plate by using either a
            violin bow to excite the plate, or place it on a wave generator and
            set it to specific frequencies. What you will observe are the
            beautiful patterns generated as shown in the figure. This experiment
            sounds relatively simple, but as simple as it sounds, this
            experiment reveals some extremely complex and intensive underlying
            mathematical principles.
          </p>
          <p>
            Ok, so how does this work? Well, it turns out these are examples of
            standing waves in the two-dimensional space. In one dimension, a
            &ldquo;node&rdquo; in a
            <a class="url" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Standing_wave"
              >standing wave</a
            >
            is a point along the wave where the amplitude is at minimum. Similarly,
            in two dimensions, there are &ldquo;nodal lines,&rdquo; which are static
            points or lines on the plate where the particles settle.
          </p>
          <a
            style="text-align: center;"
            href="articles/the-quest-to-finding-chladni-patterns-1/"
            class="redirect-button"
          >
            Read More
          </a>
        </div>
        <div id="chladni-outer-div">
          <img
            style="width: 75%; border-radius: 10px;"
            class="image"
            id="chladniImage"
            alt="Chladni plate"
            src="/public/Images/chladni-patterns-sbs.webp"
          />
          <figcaption class="caption">
            Chladni Patterns on a Square Plate.
          </figcaption>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h1 class="home-title">Posts</h1>
      <div id="post-container"></div>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h1 class="home-title">Articles</h1>
      <div id="rec-article-container"></div>
    </section>
  </div>

  <!-- Page-specific scripts -->
  <Fragment slot="scripts">
    <script is:inline>
      fetch("/assets/json/articles.json")
        .then((response) => response.json())
        .then((data) => {
          const articles = data.articles;
          article(articles.length, true, false);
        })
        .catch((error) => console.error("Error loading JSON:", error));
      document.addEventListener("DOMContentLoaded", loadPosts);
    </script>
    <script is:inline src="/assets/js/canvas-banner.js"></script>
  </Fragment>
</BaseLayout>
